  "title": "Severe Cramps?",
  "category": "Symptom Checker",
  "imageUrl": "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhbc0dd5VDTUUiLJm5m0tyXuz4MCzt4-jP4ULS7dC5iWjYhSK1uYc8vzY_2lkee8FZLkbHt0iWMX_sLGugshESicgk5iBksA6JdMznCK1rLZVG0bH_BR-uRiMDgrxYz-vx0PzXFHLVkR9xL-96drNDTtAb36rGaz7Qc1qA23Zr7fzviP6H-PrMWbV4QzJvT/s1200/Gemini_Generated_Image_nrg2runrg2runrg2.png",
  "description": "When to worry about period pain.",
  "fullContent": "### Understanding Period Cramps\n\nPeriod cramps, medically known as dysmenorrhea, occur when the uterus contracts to shed its lining during menstruation. Mild to moderate cramping is common and usually begins shortly before or during the first few days of a period.\n\n### What Is Considered Normal?\n\nNormal period cramps typically:\n\n• Start 1–2 days before or during menstruation\n• Improve after the first few days of bleeding\n• Respond to rest, heat, hydration, or over-the-counter pain relief\n• Do not significantly interfere with daily activities\n\nMany people experience cramping in the lower abdomen, lower back, hips, or thighs.\n\n### Signs Your Cramps May Be More Serious\n\nWhile painful periods are common, severe pain should never be ignored.\n\nYou should consider speaking with a healthcare professional if:\n\n• Pain prevents you from attending school, work, or daily activities\n• Pain is worsening each month\n• Pain does not improve with medication\n• You experience heavy bleeding or large blood clots\n• Pain occurs outside of your menstrual period\n• You experience pain during intercourse\n• You have unexplained pelvic pain throughout the month\n\n### Conditions That Can Cause Severe Period Pain\n\n#### Endometriosis\n\nEndometriosis occurs when tissue similar to the uterine lining grows outside the uterus. This condition can cause severe cramps, pelvic pain, fatigue, and fertility challenges.\n\n#### Adenomyosis\n\nAdenomyosis occurs when uterine lining tissue grows into the muscular wall of the uterus. It can lead to heavy bleeding and extremely painful periods.\n\n#### Fibroids\n\nFibroids are non-cancerous growths within or around the uterus. Depending on their size and location, they may contribute to heavy bleeding and severe cramps.\n\n#### Pelvic Inflammatory Disease (PID)\n\nCertain infections affecting reproductive organs can cause pelvic pain, abnormal discharge, fever, and painful menstruation.\n\n### What Can Help?\n\nMany people find relief through:\n\n• Applying a heating pad to the lower abdomen\n• Gentle stretching or yoga\n• Light exercise such as walking\n• Adequate sleep\n• Staying hydrated\n• Managing stress levels\n• Tracking symptoms in a menstrual health app\n\n### When To Seek Urgent Medical Care\n\nSeek immediate medical attention if you experience:\n\n• Sudden severe pelvic pain\n• Fever with pelvic pain\n• Fainting or dizziness\n• Very heavy bleeding that soaks through pads rapidly\n• Severe pain during pregnancy or suspected pregnancy\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nMild cramps are common, but severe pain is not something you simply have to tolerate. Understanding your symptoms and seeking medical advice when necessary can help identify underlying conditions and improve quality of life."
