  "title": "Late Period But Negative Pregnancy Test",
  "category": "Symptom Checker",
  "imageUrl": "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiQKKGjLc5XJj1WZY9NgxH4Et0PGYXUttQAkb8s_v_FdEsCgz_9B-gc65UoFpBKoW_LjJr0nBXZiWzeXrte25HOe-ujS0GjrHS4vaMPYf9fwbtgm_f3JiN2VvzbBDlkWpw1al9HWhEOYa4zbgzA_fOklxfrMHF2jO6r3C-Tg99YQdmTKT0NcKZoQ8Luto-0/s320/Gemini_Generated_Image_nnrltnnrltnnrltn.png",
  "description": "Why your period is late even when pregnancy tests are negative.",
  "fullContent": "### Why This Happens\n\nA late period with a negative pregnancy test is surprisingly common. While pregnancy is often the first concern, many other factors can delay menstruation.\n\n### Possible Causes\n\n• Stress and anxiety\n• Delayed ovulation\n• Recent illness\n• Significant weight changes\n• Excessive exercise\n• Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)\n• Thyroid disorders\n• Certain medications\n\n### Could The Test Be Wrong?\n\nPregnancy tests detect hCG hormone. Testing too early may result in a false negative because hormone levels may still be low.\n\n### When To Retest\n\nIf your period remains absent, consider retesting after a few days according to the instructions on the pregnancy test.\n\n### When To See A Doctor\n\nSeek medical advice if your period is absent for more than 90 days, or if irregular cycles become frequent.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nA negative pregnancy test does not automatically explain a late period. Hormones, stress, lifestyle changes, and medical conditions can all affect cycle timing."
