  "category": "Symptom Checker",
  "imageUrl": "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjcMebc15esRTfffSXTb5C1j7HjuLYeVtgpUikZHI5hn2-KfSRTRowPnpZGfnBq1uKl-oYgjBVYQ86HqQdzeW70vEw1iHEyHAtxi3OPLlrXcq8D7fva3qGudhmBXvsorK57HANU9CvsPDxbHxWevJsdLVrHflMWG9kt1GdWsxlxZLDl9ykRlt4jKakwIqX0/s1200/Gemini_Generated_Image_w5ezhtw5ezhtw5ez%20(1).png",
  "description": "What brown discharge means and when to worry.",
  "fullContent": "### Why Is It Brown?\n\nBrown discharge is usually older blood that has taken longer to leave the body. As blood is exposed to oxygen, it darkens from red to brown.\n\n### Common Causes\n\n• Beginning of a period\n• End of a period\n• Ovulation spotting\n• Hormonal changes\n• Birth control use\n• Perimenopause\n\n### When It May Need Attention\n\nSee a healthcare provider if brown discharge is accompanied by:\n\n• Strong odor\n• Fever\n• Severe pelvic pain\n• Itching or irritation\n• Heavy bleeding\n\n### Pregnancy Considerations\n\nSome individuals notice light brown spotting during early pregnancy. However, any concerning symptoms during pregnancy should be discussed with a healthcare professional.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nBrown discharge is often simply old blood leaving the uterus and is usually not a cause for concern."
