  "category": "Symptom Checker",
  "imageUrl": "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgD03oMYSKM8r3jpfbClo1SRAKYBubtV94VRI1xgc9rDIo3VZoMVJXFnVwDMJTyaIxELKo2eoVLuTiZ0Q8tSk8BmtJTlcwR8GRAkXuVWRkadSNydWWKzVL63Qizs1Ywc3lhLW8QZ1PIR8TRAZsg_SUPCHYXbKacOrXaczw6QpSRiBR9vTf51Bpo0rf6l9N3/s1200/Gemini_Generated_Image_mfxejxmfxejxmfxe.png",
  "description": "Why you feel exhausted around your period.",
  "fullContent": "### Understanding Cycle-Related Fatigue\n\nFeeling tired before or during your period is common. Hormonal shifts, sleep changes, and blood loss can all contribute.\n\n### Common Reasons\n\n• PMS\n• Poor sleep quality\n• Iron deficiency\n• Heavy menstrual bleeding\n• Stress\n• Low calorie intake\n• Dehydration\n\n### Signs Iron Levels May Be Low\n\n• Fatigue\n• Weakness\n• Dizziness\n• Shortness of breath\n• Pale skin\n\n### Helpful Strategies\n\n• Stay hydrated\n• Eat iron-rich foods\n• Prioritize sleep\n• Include protein at meals\n• Engage in light physical activity\n\n### When To See A Doctor\n\nPersistent exhaustion, fainting, severe weakness, or symptoms affecting daily life should be medically evaluated.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nWhile some tiredness during the menstrual cycle is normal, extreme fatigue may indicate an underlying issue such as heavy bleeding, iron deficiency, or another health condition."
