  "description": "Understand how stress can affect ovulation and delay menstruation.",
  "fullContent": "### Can Stress Really Delay A Period?\n\nYes. Stress is one of the most common causes of a late period.\n\nWhen you're under emotional or physical stress, your body produces more cortisol, often called the stress hormone. High cortisol levels can interfere with the hormones responsible for ovulation.\n\n### How It Happens\n\nThe menstrual cycle is controlled by communication between the brain and ovaries. Stress can disrupt this communication and delay ovulation.\n\nIf ovulation happens later than usual, your period will also arrive later.\n\n### Common Sources Of Stress\n\n• Exams and studies\n• Work pressure\n• Relationship problems\n• Financial concerns\n• Lack of sleep\n• Illness or injury\n• Major life changes\n\n### Signs Stress May Be Affecting Your Cycle\n\n• Late period\n• Increased PMS symptoms\n• Mood swings\n• Fatigue\n• Trouble sleeping\n• Anxiety\n\n### What Can Help?\n\n• Prioritize sleep\n• Practice relaxation techniques\n• Exercise regularly\n• Maintain healthy eating habits\n• Consider stress-management strategies\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nA stressful month can easily delay ovulation and push your period back by days or even weeks."
