  "id": "late_period_unprotected_sex",
  "title": "Late Period After Unprotected Sex",
  "category": "Late Period",
  "imageUrl": "https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg_YQx9BcQRJ75LapYL4-Apf30q7MUuGuBxX9obFHsL-U-TUfbkRrhE8H_bzZHxQK4GjRfQLosl9se5FRHcpenVoFYVFBcgfBicUpz2v0NoWXKAomK2drxrg-q3QSV2g-tovGLcciTc7KNgGPwKHGsM6z963azEZvckPBITf7i2qN8yGzAILHZ2oGyYNZjk/s1200/Gemini_Generated_Image_trdzdytrdzdytrdz.png",
  "description": "When a late period could be related to pregnancy.",
  "fullContent": "### Should You Be Concerned?\n\nIf you've had unprotected sex and your period is late, pregnancy is one possibility that should be considered.\n\n### Early Pregnancy Symptoms\n\nSome people notice:\n\n• Missed period\n• Breast tenderness\n• Nausea\n• Fatigue\n• Frequent urination\n• Food aversions\n\n### When To Take A Pregnancy Test\n\nPregnancy tests are most accurate after a missed period. Testing too early may lead to a false negative result.\n\n### Other Possible Causes\n\nEven if pregnancy tests are negative, other factors can delay menstruation:\n\n• Stress\n• Illness\n• Hormonal changes\n• PCOS\n• Thyroid disorders\n\n### When To Seek Medical Advice\n\nIf your period remains absent and pregnancy tests remain negative, consider consulting a healthcare professional.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nA late period after unprotected sex deserves attention, but pregnancy is not the only possible explanation."
