  "description": "Hormonal contraceptives can affect cycle timing.",
  "fullContent": "### Is This Normal?\n\nYes. Changes in birth control are one of the most common reasons for cycle irregularities.\n\n### Why It Happens\n\nHormonal contraceptives affect estrogen and progesterone levels. When starting, stopping, or switching methods, the body may need time to adjust.\n\n### Common Changes\n\n• Late periods\n• Missed periods\n• Spotting\n• Lighter bleeding\n• Heavier bleeding temporarily\n\n### How Long Can It Last?\n\nMany people regain their typical cycle within a few months, though timing varies.\n\n### When To Contact A Doctor\n\nSeek medical advice if:\n\n• Periods remain absent for several months\n• You have severe symptoms\n• You suspect pregnancy\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nBirth control changes often temporarily affect menstrual timing and do not necessarily indicate a health problem."
